3.3 Gender-Adversarial Auto-Encoder with
Laplace noise
We improve the gender concealment capability of the AAE by applying the Laplace mechanism to the latent space learned by the encoder. More specifically, during training, we pass the latent embedding z through a Laplace layer ùëëùëù (¬∑) that adds to its input a noisy vector n ‚àº Laplace (0, Œîùëì /ùúñ). Figure 1 graphically depicts the system.
As there is no prior bound on the ‚Ñì1-norm of the vector z, we use the same clipping procedure described in [1]: it consists in scaling z by a coefficient 1/max (1, ‚à•z‚à•1/ùê∂), where ùê∂ is the clipping threshold. This method ensures that if ‚à•ùëß ‚à•1 ‚â§ ùê∂, z remains unchanged, while if ‚à•ùëß ‚à•1 > ùê∂, it is scaled down to have a norm of ùê∂. The purpose of the clipping is to ensure that the sensitivity between any pair of vectors z and z‚Ä≤ is Œîùëì ‚â§ 2ùê∂. In practice, one pragmatic approach to determine an appropriate value for ùê∂ is to compute the median of the norm of unclipped z vectors throughout the training phase. Thus, the Laplace layer is defined as

z

